revision.text:
The '''1982–83 El Niño event''' was one of the strongest [[El Niño]] events since records were kept.

It led to widespread flooding across the southern [[United States]], droughts in [[Indonesia]] and [[Australia]], and lack of snow in northern areas of the United States. The estimated economic impact was over [[United States dollar|US$]]8 billion.<ref name="MyUser_Fcst-office.com_July_22_2015c">{{cite web|url=http://www.fcst-office.com/HardRock/Meteo241/El%20Nino%201982-1983/ProjectThree.html|title=The 1982-83 El Nino|date=|newspaper=Fcst-office.com|author=|accessdate=July 22, 2015}}</ref> This El Niño event also led to an abnormal number of [[1983 Pacific hurricane season|hurricanes in the Pacific Ocean]] during this time span; the [[Hurricane Iwa|strongest hurricane up to 1983]] hit [[Hawaii]] during this El Niño event.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/capital-weather-gang/wp/2015/06/12/how-the-super-el-nino-of-1982-83-kept-itself-a-secret/|title=How the super El Nino of 1982-83 kept itself a secret|last=Williams|first=Jack|date=2015-06-12|newspaper=The Washington Post|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|access-date=2016-10-28}}</ref>

[[File:Hoover Dam and Arizona Spillway, 1983.jpg|thumb|The snow and rainstorms brought by the 1982–83 El Niño event overflowed [[Lake Powell]] and [[Lake Mead]].]]

It led to declines of 77% among [[Galapagos penguin|Galápagos penguins]] and 49% among flightless [[cormorant]]s.<ref name="MyUser_Onlinelibrary.wiley.com_July_22_2015c">{{cite journal |title=The impact of the 1982–1983 El Niño-Southern Oscillation on seabirds in the Galapagos Islands, Ecuador |doi=10.1029/JC092iC13p14437 |bibcode=1987JGR....9214437V |volume=92 |issue = C13|journal=Journal of Geophysical Research |page=14437|year=1987 |last1=Valle |first1=Carlos A |last2=Cruz |first2=Felipe |last3=Cruz |first3=Justine B |last4=Merlen |first4=Godfrey |last5=Coulter |first5=Malcolm C }}</ref> In addition to these losses in penguins and cormorants, this El Niño event caused a quarter of adult native [[sea lion]]s and [[fur seal]]s on [[Peru|Peru's]] coast to starve, while the entirety of both seals' pup populations perished.  In the [[Galápagos Islands]], the event killed much of the [[Seaweed|macroalgae]] in the area,<ref name=IUCN>{{Cite journal |url=http://www.iucnredlist.org/details/full/63585/0 |title=Desmarestia tropica |year=2007 |website=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species |language=English |access-date=10 December 2017 |doi=10.2305/IUCN.UK.2007.RLTS.T63585A12684515.en }}</ref> and ''[[Desmarestia tropica]]'' is now possibly [[extinction|extinct]] from [[overgrazing]] by [[herbivore]]s caused by [[overfishing]] of [[predation|predator]] fish resulting from the event.<ref name="Edgar">{{cite journal|last1=Edgar|first1=G. J.|last2=Banks|first2=S. A.|last3=Brandt|first3=M.|last4=Bustamante|first4=R. H.|last5=Chiriboga|first5=A.|last6=Earle|first6=S. A.|last7=Garske|first7=L. E.|last8=Glynn|first8=P. W.|last9=Grove|first9=J. S.|last10=Henderson|first10=S.|last11=Hickman|first11=C. P.|last12=Miller|first12=K. A.|last13=Rivera|first13=F.|last14=Wellington|first14=G. M.|title=El Niño, grazers and fisheries interact to greatly elevate extinction risk for Galapagos marine species|journal=Global Change Biology|date=19 August 2010|volume=16|issue=10|pages=2876–2890|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2486.2009.02117.x|language=English|issn=1354-1013|oclc=660819334|quote=''Desmarestia tropica'' Tropical acidweed * EF$, herbivore overgrazing associated with interactions between El Niño and overfishing|bibcode=2010GCBio..16.2876E}}</ref> In [[Ecuador]], heavy rainfall and flooding led to high [[fish]] and [[shrimp]] harvests; however, the large amounts of standing water also allowed [[mosquito]] populations to thrive, leading to large outbreaks of [[malaria]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/Features/ElNino/elnino2.php|title=What is El Nino? Fact Sheet : Feature Articles|last=David|first=Herring,|date=1999-04-27|website=earthobservatory.nasa.gov|language=en|access-date=2016-10-28}}</ref>

